04538nam a22005175i 9780226520568DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226520568  a(DE-B1597)524926  a(OCoLC)489137778  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aMerolla, Jennifer L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy at Risk :bHow Terrorist Threats Affect the Public /cElizabeth J. Zechmeister, Jennifer L. Merolla. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b23 line drawings, 16 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Coping with the Threat of Terrorism -- t2. Crisis Creation: A Methodological Tour -- t3. Love Thy Neighbor? Terror Threat and the Social Fabric -- t4. Holding Out for a Hero: Looking for Leadership in Times of Terror Threat -- t5. Enabling Charismatic Leadership in Times of Terror Threat -- t6. Engage Abroad, Protect at Home -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Question Wordings and Codings -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do threats of terrorism affect the opinions of citizens? Speculation abounds, but until now no one had marshaled hard evidence to explain the complexities of this relationship. Drawing on data from surveys and original experiments they conducted in the United States and Mexico, Jennifer Merolla and Elizabeth Zechmeister demonstrate how our strategies for coping with terrorist threats significantly influence our attitudes toward fellow citizens, political leaders, and foreign nations. The authors reveal, for example, that some people try to restore a sense of order and control through increased wariness of others—especially of those who exist outside the societal mainstream. Additionally, voters under threat tend to prize “strong leadership” more highly than partisan affiliation, making some politicians seem more charismatic than they otherwise would. The authors show that a wary public will sometimes continue to empower such leaders after they have been elected, giving them greater authority even at the expense of institutional checks and balances. Having demonstrated that a climate of terrorist threat also increases support for restrictive laws at home and engagement against terrorists abroad, Merolla and Zechmeister conclude that our responses to such threats can put democracy at risk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aterrorism, fear, threats, public opinion, violence, attack, security, nonfiction, sociology, politics, history, order, control, difference, racism, charismatic leaders, cult of personality, politicians, party affiliation, partisan, leadership, strength, authority, checks and balances, government, power, restriction, law, legislation, policy, prevention, voting, electorate, psychology, heroism, masculinity, gender.1 aZechmeister, Elizabeth J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022652054440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226520568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226520568/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  